Subject: blunt megasclere [PORO:0000172]
Value: Adjective referring to the extremities of megascleres. See OXEA.

Subject: conical megasclere [PORO:0000230]
Value: Adjective referring to the extremities of megascleres. See OXEA.

Subject: equal megasclere [PORO:0000293]
Value: Adjective referring to the extremities of megascleres. See OXEA.

Subject: symmetrical megasclere [PORO:0000577]
Value: Adjective referring to the extremities of megascleres. See OXEA.

Subject: asymmetric megasclere [PORO:0000154]

Subject: stepped megasclere [PORO:0000556]
Value: Adjective referring to the extremities of a megasclere. See OXEA.

Subject: spicule [PORO:0000017]
Value: siliceous or calcareous entities that form the mineral skeleton of a sponge

Subject: lophocyte [PORO:0000005]
Value: amoeba-like cells that move slowly through the mesohyl and secrete collagen fibres.

Subject: micromere [PORO:0000009]
Value: anterior ciliated cell of the sponge larva that will differentiate into a choanocyte or spicule-forming cell

Subject: sclerocyte [PORO:0000011]
Value: spicule secreting cells, found in sponges. They secrete calcareous or siliceous spicules which are found in the mesohyl layer of sponges. The sclerocytes produce spicules via formation of a cellular triad

Subject: myocyte [PORO:0000014]
Value: conduct signals and cause parts of the animal to contract. They are assumed to regulate the flow of water by increasing or decreasing the diameter of these openings to the aquiferous system.

Subject: gray cell [PORO:0000015]
Value: cells that acts as sponges' equivalent of an immune system.

Subject: archaeocyte [PORO:0000016]
Value: amoeba-like large cells with large nuclei that are totipotent. They also have important roles in feeding and in clearing debris that block the ostia.

Subject: spicule [PORO:0000017]
Value: siliceous or calcareous entities that form the mineral skeleton of a sponge

Subject: osculum [PORO:0000018]
Value: an excretory structure in the living sponge, a large opening to the outside through which the current of water exits after passing through the spongocoel. Wastes diffuse into the water and the water exits through the osculum at a velocity of nearly 8.4 cm/second, carrying away with it the sponge's wastes. The size of the osculum is regulated by the myocyte. Its size, in turn, determines the amount of water flowing through the sponge.

Subject: spongeocoel [PORO:0000020]
Value: large, central cavity of sponges. Water enters the spongocoel through hundreds of tiny pores (Ostia) and exits through the larger opening (osculum). Depending on the body plan of the sponge (which can be asconoid, syconoid, or leuconoid), the spongocoel could be a simple interior space of the sponge or a complexly branched inner structure. Regardless of body plan or class, the spongocoel is lined with choanocytes, which have flagella that push water through the spongocoel, creating a current.

Subject: pinacocyte [PORO:0000023]
Value: flat cells found on the outermost layer of sponges. They can expand and contract to slightly alter the size of the sponge, and can also produce collagen. Delimits the sponge from the external milieu and always only in a layer one-cell deep

Subject: prosopyle [PORO:0000024]
Value: a pore through which water is drawn from the outside into one of the saclike chambers formed by the evagination of the body wall.

Subject: porocyte [PORO:0000044]
Value: cell that surrounds a pore (ostium). In an asconoid sponge, water enters the sponge through the porocytes, passes directly to the choanocyte-lined spongocoel, and then out of the sponge through the osculum.

Subject: apopyle [PORO:0000046]
Value: a pore in each of the saclike chambers formed by the evagination of the body wall, through which water passes into the excurrent canals.

Subject: aster [PORO:0000902]
Value: stellate spicule where where 1-6 primary rays undergo terminal branching to form secondary rays (differs from definition used for desmosponges)

Subject: silicatein [PORO:0000960]
Value: enzyme which catalyzes the formation of silicate polymers

Subject: silicase [PORO:0000961]
Value: enzyme in sponges, proposed to be involved in silica restructuring and maintenance. The proposed mechanism involves bound zinc acting as a Lewis acid catalyst to break the silicate ester bond between silicon and oxygen

Subject: acantho [PORO:0002001]
Value: has spines; applies only to spicules
